This dataset is a sample of logs of user behavior events streamed from a social marketplace or a C2C platform data.

it collects:

  • which users are viewing which products/users, when, and on what device
  • server assignments of A/B testing experiments and groups

two distinct types of tables:

  • item (dimension)
  • event (fact)

--> both joined by ITEM primary key 'id' and EVENT foreign key 'parameter_value'

1. Item¶

  • dimension table: product catalog
  • describes what is being sold on the platform
  • adjective + category + modifier = name

2.B. Parse JSON Payload¶

In [10]:
if events_df is not None:

    # 1. Define a robust JSON parsing function
    def parse_json(payload):
        try:
            return json.loads(payload)
        except (json.JSONDecodeError, TypeError):
            return None # Return None for bad data or nulls

    # 2. Apply the function to each row
    payloads = events_df['event.payload'].apply(parse_json)

    # 3. Drop rows where JSON parsing failed
    original_count = len(payloads)
    payloads = payloads.dropna()
    print(f"Successfully parsed {len(payloads)} rows.")
    print(f"Dropped {original_count - len(payloads)} rows with bad/missing JSON.")

    # 4. Convert the resulting Series of dictionaries into a new DataFrame
    payload_df = pd.DataFrame(payloads.tolist())

    # 5. Concatenate the new payload columns with the original DataFrame
    events_df_flat = pd.concat([events_df.loc[payloads.index].drop('event.payload', axis=1), payload_df.set_index(payloads.index)], axis=1)

    print("--- Flattened DataFrame (events.csv) ---")
    display(events_df_flat.head())

    print("\n--- New Data Types and Nulls (events.csv) ---")
    events_df_flat.info()
else:
    print("events_df not loaded. Skipping JSON parsing.")
    events_df_flat = None # Set to None so subsequent cells can check

Drill down analysis of parameters values¶

  • users can either view other users or items
  • referrers metrics (home, shopping cart, etc.)
  • some users are assigned experiments (test_id) for some features (e.g. search algorithms, buttons, feed, etc..)
  • each test assignment is divided in a control group and test group (A/B testing)

if 'events_df_flat' in locals() and events_df_flat is not None and not events_df_flat.empty:

Analysis of the 3pm spike¶

  • top 10 users: pattern of 12 events each
  • platform: server
  • event_time: 15h23
  • parameter_name: test_assignment, test_id

--> daily scheduled backend job each day at 15h22-3

--> massively parallel distributed batch job (likely spark)

--> purpose: A/B test assignments to users by the server

--> needs to be filtered out for user behavior analysis

--> df_real_users = events_df_flat[events_df_flat['platform'] != 'server']

In [18]:
if events_df_flat is not None:
    try:
        # Ensure the datetime and hour columns exist before filtering
        if 'event_hour' not in events_df_flat.columns:
            print("Creating 'event_hour' column...")
            events_df_flat['event_time'] = pd.to_datetime(events_df_flat['event_time'])
            events_df_flat['event_hour'] = events_df_flat['event_time'].dt.hour
            print("Done.")

        # 1. Filter the DataFrame for only the 3 PM spike
        df_3pm = events_df_flat[events_df_flat['event_hour'] == 15]
        
        if df_3pm.empty:
            print("No events found for hour 15. The spike might be at a different hour.")
        else:
            print(f"--- Analysis of {len(df_3pm)} Events at 3 PM ---")

            # 2. Check for suspicious patterns:
            
            # Is it all one user? (e.g., a 'service-account' user)
            print("\n--- Top 10 Users at 3 PM ---")
            print(df_3pm['user_id'].value_counts().head(10))

            # Is it all one platform?
            print("\n--- Platforms at 3 PM ---")
            print(df_3pm['platform'].value_counts())

            # Do all events happen at exactly 15:00:00?
            print("\n--- Event Minutes at 3 PM ---")
            # This checks if they all piled up in the first minute of the hour
            print(df_3pm['event_time'].dt.minute.value_counts().head())
            
            # --- NEW ANALYSIS: What is this job DOING? ---
            
            print("\n--- Event Names during 3 PM spike ---")
            # This will likely show 'test_assignment' is the dominant event
            print(df_3pm['event_name'].value_counts())
            
            print("\n--- Parameter Names during 3 PM spike ---")
            param_names_3pm = df_3pm['parameter_name'].value_counts()
            print(param_names_3pm)
            
            # Now, let's look at the values for the top parameter names
            
            if 'test_assignment' in param_names_3pm.index:
                print("\n--- Values for 'test_assignment' (at 3 PM) ---")
                print(df_3pm[df_3pm['parameter_name'] == 'test_assignment']['parameter_value'].value_counts())

            if 'test_id' in param_names_3pm.index:
                print("\n--- Values for 'test_id' (at 3 PM) ---")
                print(df_3pm[df_3pm['parameter_name'] == 'test_id']['parameter_value'].value_counts())
                
            # Check if any 'view_item' events are also in this spike
            if 'item_id' in param_names_3pm.index:
                print(f"\n--- Found {param_names_3pm['item_id']} 'view_item' events in spike ---")
                print("--- Top 5 'item_id's viewed (at 3 PM) ---")
                print(df_3pm[df_3pm['parameter_name'] == 'item_id']['parameter_value'].value_counts().head())
            # --- END NEW ANALYSIS ---

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during analysis: {e}")
        print("Please ensure 'events_df_flat' is loaded correctly.")

try:
    event_item_ids = events_df_flat[
        events_df_flat['parameter_name'] == 'item_id']['parameter_value'].astype(float).unique()
    
    # 2. Get all item IDs from the item catalog
    catalog_item_ids = item_df['id'].unique()

    # 3. Check for referential integrity (are all event items in the catalog?)
    is_in_catalog = pd.Series(event_item_ids).isin(catalog_item_ids)
    all_items_exist = is_in_catalog.all()

    print(f"All item IDs from the event sample exist in item.csv: {all_items_exist}")

    if not all_items_exist:
        missing_ids = event_item_ids[~is_in_catalog]
        print("\n--- Missing Item IDs ---")
        print(f"Found {len(missing_ids)} item IDs that were viewed but are NOT in item.csv.")
        print("Showing up to 10 missing IDs:")
        print(missing_ids[:10])
        
except ValueError as e:
